3. Git Commit Message Guidelines
To ensure code quality, traceability, and smooth collaboration, all participants are required to
follow the commit message format below.
Commits that do not follow this format may be rejected during code review.
3.1. Commit Message Format
<type>(<scope>): <short description>
[optional body]
Example (Simple Commit)
feat(auth): add biometric login support
Example (Commit With Body)
chore(survey): update dialog styling and button text
- apply theme-based styling to end-day dialog
- change button text from "Continue" to "Confirm"
- improve color consistency for better UX
3.2. Commit Types (Mandatory)
Type Description
feat Add a new feature
fix Fix a bug
chore Maintenance tasks or dependency updates
refactor Code restructuring without behavior change
style Formatting only (no logic change)
docs Documentation updates
test Add or update tests
perf Performance improvements
ci CI/CD configuration or scripts
revert Revert a previous commit
3.3. Commit Scopes
Use a scope to indicate which part of the system is affected.
Commonly Used Scopes
auth, survey, dashboard, profile, api, ui, navigation, storage, notification, location, camera,
forms, deps, config, security
Scope Example
fix(api): handle empty response for user endpoint
3.4. Commit Description Rules
Commit descriptions must follow these rules:
Use imperative mood
(e.g., add, fix, update)
Start with lowercase letters
Be 50 characters or fewer
Be clear and specific
3.5. Non-Compliant Commits
Commits that do not follow these guidelines:
May be requested to be rewritten
May be rejected during code review
Can negatively impact team evaluation in the hackathon
3.6. Final Note
Maintaining clean repositories and structured commit messages reflects professional engineering
practices and helps judges and mentors review your work efficiently.
All teams are expected to treat their repositories as production-grade projects